</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Hemoperitoneum may occur in various emergent conditions. In the trauma setting, evidence of intraperitoneal blood depicted at computed tomography (CT) should lead the radiologist to conduct a careful search of images for the injured visceral organ (the liver or spleen). Specific CT signs, such as a sentinel clot or extravasation of intravascular contrast material, may indicate the source of bleeding and help direct management. In addition, the configuration of accumulated blood may help identify the injured organ; for example, triangular fluid collections are observed in the mesentery most often in the setting of bowel or mesenteric injury. Less commonly, hemoperitoneum may have a nontraumatic origin. Iatrogenic hemoperitoneum may occur as a complication of surgery or other interventional procedures in the abdominal cavity or as a result of anticoagulation therapy. Hemoperitoneum also may be seen in the setting of blood dyscrasias such as hemophilia and polycythemia vera. Tumor-associated hemorrhage, which most often occurs in hepatocellular carcinoma, hepatic adenoma, or vascular metastatic disease, also may produce hemoperitoneum. Other potential causes of nontraumatic hemoperitoneum are gynecologic conditions such as hemorrhage or rupture of an ovarian cyst and rupture of the gestational sac in ectopic pregnancy, and hepatic hematoma in syndromic hemolysis with elevated liver enzymes and low platelet count (HELLP syndrome). Vascular lesions (visceral artery aneurysms and pseudoaneurysms) that occur in systemic vascular diseases such as Ehlers-Danlos syndrome or in pancreatitis are another less common source of hemoperitoneum.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2007</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.271065042">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.271065042">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g01a.jpeg" height="1092" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1a.</b>  Typical flow pattern of hemorrhage from a liver laceration. <b>(a)</b> Contrast material–enhanced CT image shows high-attenuation fluid (arrows) in perihepatic and perisplenic regions, the hepatorenal fossa, and the lesser sac. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image at a lower level than <b>a</b> shows blood tracking laterally along the paracolic gutters (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F1A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g01b.jpeg" height="1076" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1b.</b>  Typical flow pattern of hemorrhage from a liver laceration. <b>(a)</b> Contrast material–enhanced CT image shows high-attenuation fluid (arrows) in perihepatic and perisplenic regions, the hepatorenal fossa, and the lesser sac. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image at a lower level than <b>a</b> shows blood tracking laterally along the paracolic gutters (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F1B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g02a.jpeg" height="1431" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Free intraperitoneal fluid after trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large volume of high-attenuation free intraperitoneal fluid. A subsequent CT cystogram revealed that most of the fluid was urine leaking from an injured bladder. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows leakage of urine from a bladder rupture at the 1-o’clock position (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g02b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Free intraperitoneal fluid after trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large volume of high-attenuation free intraperitoneal fluid. A subsequent CT cystogram revealed that most of the fluid was urine leaking from an injured bladder. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows leakage of urine from a bladder rupture at the 1-o’clock position (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g03a.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Low-attenuation hemoperitoneum in a hemophiliac patient with a splenic rupture. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> at a lower level than <b>a</b>) show much lower attenuation in the intraperitoneal hemorrhage than in the adjacent muscle. The patient’s hematocrit level was 0.24 at the time of CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g03b.jpeg" height="1515" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Low-attenuation hemoperitoneum in a hemophiliac patient with a splenic rupture. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>b</b> at a lower level than <b>a</b>) show much lower attenuation in the intraperitoneal hemorrhage than in the adjacent muscle. The patient’s hematocrit level was 0.24 at the time of CT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g04a.jpeg" height="1364" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Sentinel clot sign. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a sentinel clot secondary to laceration along the fissure for the ligamentum teres (arrow), in the perihepatic space and lesser sac. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a patient who was undergoing anticoagulation therapy for a protein C deficiency shows a sentinel clot (arrow) surrounding the spleen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g04b.jpeg" height="1287" width="1584" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Sentinel clot sign. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a sentinel clot secondary to laceration along the fissure for the ligamentum teres (arrow), in the perihepatic space and lesser sac. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image obtained in a patient who was undergoing anticoagulation therapy for a protein C deficiency shows a sentinel clot (arrow) surrounding the spleen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g05a.jpeg" height="1412" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Bleeding hepatoma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows perihepatic and perisplenic fluid, with an area of slightly higher attenuation (arrow) indicative of a clot along the left hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows the origin of the clot, a ruptured mass (arrow) that subsequently was proved to be a hepatocellular carcinoma, as well as active extravasation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g05b.jpeg" height="1518" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Bleeding hepatoma. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows perihepatic and perisplenic fluid, with an area of slightly higher attenuation (arrow) indicative of a clot along the left hepatic lobe. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows the origin of the clot, a ruptured mass (arrow) that subsequently was proved to be a hepatocellular carcinoma, as well as active extravasation (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g06x.jpeg" height="1624" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Hematocrit effect. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows an obvious layer of high attenuation produced by sedimented blood cells (arrow) in a pelvic hemoperitoneum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g07a.jpeg" height="1574" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Active arterial extravasation. Note the sentinel clot sign produced by serpiginous areas of high attenuation surrounded by lower-attenuation areas of hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows active bleeding from a branch of the internal iliac artery (arrow) in a patient with pelvic fractures. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows active bleeding from a splenic rupture due to blunt trauma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g07b.jpeg" height="1363" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Active arterial extravasation. Note the sentinel clot sign produced by serpiginous areas of high attenuation surrounded by lower-attenuation areas of hematoma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows active bleeding from a branch of the internal iliac artery (arrow) in a patient with pelvic fractures. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows active bleeding from a splenic rupture due to blunt trauma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g08x.jpeg" height="1592" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8.</b>  Mesenteric tear. Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts high-attenuation triangular fluid collections (arrows) within the mesentery of the distal small bowel in a patient with a surgically proved ileal mesenteric tear.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g09a.jpeg" height="1433" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Spectrum of hepatic and splenic injuries due to trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large subcapsular hepatic hematoma with laceration and periportal edema and with a typical indentation in the fibrous capsule of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple irregular low-attenuation contusions in both hepatic lobes (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a single hepatic laceration that extends alongside the fissure of the ligamentum teres (arrow). Lacerations commonly occur along the natural planes of hepatic vessels and fissures. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a single jagged laceration in the posterior tip of the spleen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g09b.jpeg" height="1413" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Spectrum of hepatic and splenic injuries due to trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large subcapsular hepatic hematoma with laceration and periportal edema and with a typical indentation in the fibrous capsule of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple irregular low-attenuation contusions in both hepatic lobes (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a single hepatic laceration that extends alongside the fissure of the ligamentum teres (arrow). Lacerations commonly occur along the natural planes of hepatic vessels and fissures. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a single jagged laceration in the posterior tip of the spleen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g09c.jpeg" height="1417" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Spectrum of hepatic and splenic injuries due to trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large subcapsular hepatic hematoma with laceration and periportal edema and with a typical indentation in the fibrous capsule of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple irregular low-attenuation contusions in both hepatic lobes (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a single hepatic laceration that extends alongside the fissure of the ligamentum teres (arrow). Lacerations commonly occur along the natural planes of hepatic vessels and fissures. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a single jagged laceration in the posterior tip of the spleen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g09d.jpeg" height="1421" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9d.</b>  Spectrum of hepatic and splenic injuries due to trauma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large subcapsular hepatic hematoma with laceration and periportal edema and with a typical indentation in the fibrous capsule of the liver. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows multiple irregular low-attenuation contusions in both hepatic lobes (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a single hepatic laceration that extends alongside the fissure of the ligamentum teres (arrow). Lacerations commonly occur along the natural planes of hepatic vessels and fissures. <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a single jagged laceration in the posterior tip of the spleen (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F9D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g10a.jpeg" height="1417" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Contrast-enhanced CT images at progressively lower levels show a liver laceration extending to the level of the inferior vena cava, with evidence of active extravasation and hemoperitoneum, in a patient after a motor vehicle collision. At surgery, the liver was found to be totally avulsed from the inferior vena cava, leaving the latter open at the level of the diaphragm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g10b.jpeg" height="1353" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Contrast-enhanced CT images at progressively lower levels show a liver laceration extending to the level of the inferior vena cava, with evidence of active extravasation and hemoperitoneum, in a patient after a motor vehicle collision. At surgery, the liver was found to be totally avulsed from the inferior vena cava, leaving the latter open at the level of the diaphragm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g10c.jpeg" height="1314" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Contrast-enhanced CT images at progressively lower levels show a liver laceration extending to the level of the inferior vena cava, with evidence of active extravasation and hemoperitoneum, in a patient after a motor vehicle collision. At surgery, the liver was found to be totally avulsed from the inferior vena cava, leaving the latter open at the level of the diaphragm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g11a.jpeg" height="1515" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Liver laceration with pseudoaneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large liver laceration with internal pooling of high-attenuation material (arrow), a finding suggestive of an aneurysm or pseudo-aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a pseudoaneurysm (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g11b.jpeg" height="1438" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Liver laceration with pseudoaneurysm formation. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large liver laceration with internal pooling of high-attenuation material (arrow), a finding suggestive of an aneurysm or pseudo-aneurysm. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram shows a pseudoaneurysm (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g12x.jpeg" height="1452" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12.</b>  Mesenteric tear. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows active extravasation from jejunal mesenteric vessels with associated jejunal injury and mesenteric hemorrhage indicated by a triangular region of hemoperitoneum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g13x.jpeg" height="1336" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13.</b>  Hematoma after a pancreatoduodenectomy (Whipple operation). Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large abdominal hematoma that involves the left perihepatic and perisplenic space, with evidence of active extravasation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g14x.jpeg" height="1388" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14.</b>  Hematoma after interventional procedures. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hematoma within the lesser sac after a laparoscopic Nissen fundoplication.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g15x.jpeg" height="1464" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15.</b>  Hematoma after interventional procedures. Contrast-enhanced CT image in another patient depicts a large perigastric hematoma (arrow) after a percutaneous gastrostomy tube placement.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g16a.jpeg" height="1496" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Splenic rupture. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a splenic rupture and pooling of contrast material in a patient with splenomegaly due to polycythemia vera. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram reveals multiple splenic pseudoaneurysms that were subsequently treated with embolization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g16b.jpeg" height="1296" width="1164" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Splenic rupture. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a splenic rupture and pooling of contrast material in a patient with splenomegaly due to polycythemia vera. <b>(b)</b> Angiogram reveals multiple splenic pseudoaneurysms that were subsequently treated with embolization.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g17a.jpeg" height="1441" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Ruptured hepatic angiosarcoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) show a heterogeneous low-attenuation lesion in the left hepatic lobe, with evidence of increased vascularity, active extravasation, and hemoperitoneum. At pathologic analysis, the lesion was found to be a hepatic angiosarcoma. The high-attenuation material adjacent to the lesion represents perihepatic blood secondary to a capsular rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g17b.jpeg" height="1441" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Ruptured hepatic angiosarcoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) show a heterogeneous low-attenuation lesion in the left hepatic lobe, with evidence of increased vascularity, active extravasation, and hemoperitoneum. At pathologic analysis, the lesion was found to be a hepatic angiosarcoma. The high-attenuation material adjacent to the lesion represents perihepatic blood secondary to a capsular rupture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g18x.jpeg" height="1570" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18.</b>  Hemorrhagic metastases. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked hemoperitoneum with active extravasation in a patient with metastatic peritoneal melanoma. Note the sentinel clot that surrounds the tumor implant, and the subcutaneous melanotic nodule (arrowhead) in the left posterior region.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g19x.jpeg" height="1379" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19.</b>  Hemorrhagic metastases. Contrast-enhanced CT image depicts multiple hemorrhagic hepatic lesions with central high attenuation in a patient with known metastatic testicular choriocarcinoma. Hemoperitoneum (arrow) is seen adjacent to the largest lesion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g20a.jpeg" height="1399" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F20A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20a.</b>  Ruptured hepatocellular adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large heterogeneous low-attenuation mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe, and a loss of liver capsule integrity anterolaterally. <b>(b)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image shows the peripherally enhancing mass, ruptured liver capsule, and perihepatic hemorrhage (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F20A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g20b.jpeg" height="1402" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20b.</b>  Ruptured hepatocellular adenoma. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large heterogeneous low-attenuation mass (arrow) in the right hepatic lobe, and a loss of liver capsule integrity anterolaterally. <b>(b)</b> Coronal volume-rendered CT image shows the peripherally enhancing mass, ruptured liver capsule, and perihepatic hemorrhage (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F20B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g21x.jpeg" height="1417" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21.</b>  Splenic rupture. Unenhanced CT image shows an enlarged spleen with a perisplenic sentinel clot in a patient with lymphoma and thrombocytopenia who was evaluated for flank pain.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g22x.jpeg" height="1341" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22.</b>  Splenic rupture. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hemoperitoneum that surrounds an enlarged ruptured spleen in a patient with malaria. (Fig 22 courtesy of Howard J. Harvin, MD, Scottsdale, Ariz.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g23a.jpeg" height="1457" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23a.</b>  Ruptured hemorrhagic ovarian cyst. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows an adnexal cyst with an internal hematocrit level (arrow), surrounded by a pelvic hemorrhage. A curvilinear focus of extravasation (arrowhead) visible posterior to the cyst was found at surgery to represent active bleeding from an internal iliac artery branch. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image from a different patient shows an ovarian cyst (arrow) and surrounding hemorrhage with a hematocrit effect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F23A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F23B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g23b.jpeg" height="1634" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F23B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 23b.</b>  Ruptured hemorrhagic ovarian cyst. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows an adnexal cyst with an internal hematocrit level (arrow), surrounded by a pelvic hemorrhage. A curvilinear focus of extravasation (arrowhead) visible posterior to the cyst was found at surgery to represent active bleeding from an internal iliac artery branch. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image from a different patient shows an ovarian cyst (arrow) and surrounding hemorrhage with a hematocrit effect.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F23B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g24x.jpeg" height="1564" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 24.</b>  Adnexal rupture due to an ectopic pregnancy. CT image shows a hemorrhagic right adnexal mass that corresponds to an ectopic gestational sac with associated active extravasation (arrow) and blood in the cul-de-sac (arrowhead). Ectopic pregnancy and rupture were proved at surgery. (Courtesy of Alvaro Huete, MD, Santiago, Chile.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g25x.jpeg" height="1728" width="1394" aria-labelledby="F25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 25.</b>  HELLP syndrome. Coronal CT image demonstrates a subcapsular hematoma (arrow) in a recent postpartum patient with a history of HELLP syndrome. Note the hypervascularity of the postpartum uterus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.271065042/asset/images/g07ja24g26x.jpeg" height="1406" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 26.</b>  Hemorrhagic pancreatitis. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a hematoma in the gastrocolic ligament, with a focus of active extravasation (arrow). At angiography, the bleeding vessel was found to be a pancreatic branch of the splenic artery. Subsequent embolization was successful.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.271065042&amp;id=F26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Federle</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">MP</span></span>, Goldberg HI, Kaiser JA, et al. Evaluation of trauma by computed tomography. <em>Radiology</em>1981; 138: 637–644.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiology.138.3.6450962">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6450962/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radiology&amp;publication_year=1981&amp;pages=637&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiology.138.3.6450962&amp;pmid=6450962">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="R2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Shuman</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">WP</span></span>. CT of blunt abdominal trauma in adults. <em>Radiology</em>1997; 205: 297–306.<