<div class="core-journal-description"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">27</span></span> • <span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">1</span></span> • <span property="datePublished">Jan 1 2007</span></div><div class="core-pagination"><span class="heading">Pages</span>: <span class="content"><span property="pageStart">109</span> - <span property="pageEnd">125</span></span></div><div class="core-pmid"><span class="heading">PubMed</span>: <a class="content" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17235002/" property="sameAs" target="_blank" title="Link to PubMed">17235002</a></div></div></div></section><section class="core-copyright"><h4>Copyright</h4><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2007.</div></section><section class="core-history"><h4>History</h4><div><b class="core-label">Published online</b>: Jan 1 2007</div></section><section class="core-permissions"><h4>Permissions</h4><div>Request permissions for this article.</div><div><a class="btn" href="https://marketplace.copyright.com/rs-ui-web/mp/search/all/10.1148%2Frg.271065042">Request Permissions</a></div></section><section property="keywords"><h4>Keyword</h4><ol><li><a href="/action/doSearch?AllField=HELLP+%3D+hemolysis%2C+elevated+liver+enzymes%2C+and+low+platelet+count&amp;stemming=yes&amp;publication=radiographics" alt="Search on this keyword" rel="nofollow">HELLP = hemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelet count</a></li></ol></section><section class="core-article-notes"><h4>Notes</h4><div role="paragraph">Hemoperitoneum may be seen in both traumatic and nontraumatic settings, and, by using CT, the radiologist can define the source and help direct the management of bleeding.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-autho